C19 = new(#d461c4c4-e6b1-4931-9ff3-febca0c96767#, Reviewers.R1) {
  Text: Paragraph {
    "The more I think about it the more I think the prior on H should depend on the value of λ and μ. ";
    "But in this case, why is it a marginal prior and not a prior given these parameters? ";
    "(p7 appendix) Please add some detail on that, as it might also explain why you observe more deletions and additions.";
  };
  AssignedTo(People.Huelsenbeck_John);

  Response: Paragraph {

  "The reviewer is absolutely right that, from a generative perspective, the prior on the homology structure H should depend on the insertion and deletion rates lambda and mu. ";
  "Under an explicit indel process, these parameters determine the expected sequence length and, consequently, the prior distribution over alignment lengths and homology patterns. ";
  "In particular, when insertion rates are low relative to deletion rates, shorter and more compact alignments should indeed receive higher prior probability than very long alignments. ";
  "\n\n";

  "Upon re-examining our implementation of the TKF91 model, we realized that our prior on H is not uniform, as implied by the manuscript text. ";
  "Instead, the prior probability of an alignment length follows a geometric distribution with parameter lambda divided by mu, corresponding to the equilibrium length distribution of the TKF91 model. ";
  "Thus, alignments with many columns are already down-weighted a priori, and the prior on H does depend on lambda and mu in an important and meaningful way. ";
  "In this sense, the current implementation is closer to a generative indel-based prior than our description suggested. ";
  "\n\n";

  "That said, the prior is still not fully generative in the strongest sense, because it does not explicitly model the full homology structure H as a realization of a TKF91 process conditional on lambda and mu. ";
  "Rather, it captures the equilibrium length distribution implied by the model, while remaining agnostic about finer-grained dependencies among homology patterns. ";
  "We agree that a prior constructed by explicitly generating H under the TKF91 process would be more coherent. ";
  "However, implementing such a prior in a computationally tractable way, particularly in the context of joint inference over trees, alignments, and substitution parameters, remains challenging. ";
  "\n\n";

  "We will revise the manuscript to correct the description of the prior on H and to clarify that alignment lengths are geometrically distributed with parameter lambda divided by mu, as implied by the equilibrium behavior of the TKF91 model. ";
  "We will also clarify that developing fully generative priors on homology structures conditional on indel parameters is an important direction for future work. ";
  "\n\n";

  "We have added the following sentence to the manuscript. ";
  "\n\n";

  "A more coherent alternative would be to define a fully generative prior on H conditional on lambda and mu, building directly on the TKF91 process itself. ";
  "Developing such priors for segmental homology structures remains an important direction for future work.\n\n ";

 "We also added a sentence clarifying the prior on the alignment:\n\n";
          "An alignment of length L receives a prior probability that is geometric with probability λ / μ. "; "(Under the TKF91 model, at equilibrium, the length of an alignment is geometrically distriubted with parameter λ/μ.)"; 
  };

};

