C21 = new(#8c6f45b5-fdd1-4c93-be2c-f96a92e2b4a4#, Reviewers.R1) {
  Text: Paragraph {
    "The sentence “the likelihood accounts for all the histories of insertion, deletion, and segmental substitution that could have led to the observed words sampled from the nine languages” in 5.1 ";
    "is strange to that regards. ";
    "If it accounted for all the additions and deletion possible, I think the number of possible H 3 would be infinite, as the ancestral state can have any number of deleted characters. There is an approximation here somewhere (which is fine but would be interesting to understand exactly).";
  };
  AssignedTo(People.Huelsenbeck_John);

  Response: Paragraph {

  "The reviewer is correct that, if considered naively, the space of possible insertion–deletion histories is infinite. ";
  "An ancestral sequence could in principle contain arbitrarily many characters that are later deleted. ";
  "However, this does not invalidate our statement. ";
  "The likelihood we compute does indeed account for all possible histories of insertion, deletion, and substitution, weighting each by its probability under the model. ";
  "This is not an approximation, but a standard consequence of marginalization in continuous-time stochastic processes. ";
  "\n\n";

  "Formally, the likelihood marginalizes over all unobserved evolutionary histories. ";
  "Although the set of such histories is infinite, their total contribution is finite because histories with many insertion and deletion events have vanishingly small probability under the model. ";
  "This is entirely analogous to other continuous-time Markov processes, where infinitely many event sequences are possible over any positive time interval, yet transition probabilities remain well defined. ";
  "\n\n";

  "This is the same principle that underlies likelihood calculations in simpler substitution-only models. ";
  "In programs such as MrBayes or BEAST, the likelihood integrates over all possible assignments of ancestral states at internal nodes via the Felsenstein pruning algorithm, and all possible numbers and timings of substitution events along each branch via matrix exponentiation. ";
  "Even in these models, the likelihood implicitly accounts for infinitely many substitution histories, despite the fact that only a finite state space is observed. ";
  "\n\n";

  "For models with insertions and deletions, such as TKF91, the situation is conceptually identical but computationally more challenging. ";
  "The TKF91 process defines a continuous-time birth–death model on sequence length, coupled with substitution on surviving characters. ";
  "Although an ancestral sequence may be arbitrarily long, the equilibrium length distribution is proper, and the probability of extremely long ancestral sequences decays rapidly. ";
  "The dynamic programming algorithm of Lunter et al. (2003) exploits this structure to marginalize analytically over all possible indel histories without enumerating them explicitly. ";
  "The poor scaling of the algorithm reflects the difficulty of performing this marginalization exactly, not the presence of an approximation. ";
  "\n\n";

  "Thus, while the reviewer’s intuition that there must be infinitely many histories is correct, this does not imply that the likelihood is ill-defined or approximate. ";
  "On the contrary, the likelihood is precisely defined as a sum or integral over all such histories, and this is exactly what our statement in Section 5.1 was meant to convey. ";
  };

};

C25 = new(#11995460-7bae-4185-ba13-861d7c9130f6#, Reviewers.R1) {
  Text: Paragraph {
    "I don’t think Ψ is an amazing notation for a tree.";
  };
  AssignedTo(People.Huelsenbeck_John);

  Response: Paragraph {

  "We appreciate the reviewer’s comment regarding notation. ";
  "Our use of the symbol Ψ to denote a tree is not intended to be aesthetic, but conventional. ";
  "In the phylogenetics literature, it is common to represent a phylogenetic tree as the combination of a topology, typically denoted by tau, and a set of branch lengths, often denoted by v. ";
  "The pair is then written compactly as Ψ =(t,v). ";
  "This notation is used, for example, to distinguish between the discrete combinatorial structure of the tree and its continuous branch-length parameters. ";
  "\n\n";

  "We adopted this convention to make the distinction between topology and branch lengths explicit and to remain consistent with existing usage in Bayesian phylogenetic modeling. ";
  "That said, we are not wedded to this choice of symbol and would be happy to change the notation if the editor or reviewer strongly prefers an alternative. ";
  };

};

C26 = new(#5ce04d50-ce4a-4f51-9b28-0014edbbdc54#, Reviewers.R1) {
